resource.http://dev.llgc.org.uk/sas/full_text:
The two temples of Abu Simbel, carved from the rock on a hill overlooking the Nile in Upper Egypt, were built by Ramses II, who ruled Egypt from 1298 to 1235 B.C.

In the 1950s, the High Aswan Dam (South) project is being launched by Nasser to provide the electricity needed for the region, increase cultivable areas and reduce flooding in the Nile. But the project is a danger to the monuments of Nubia, since its implementation must lead to the formation of a huge artificial lake, Nasser Lake. Many pharaonic and Greco-Roman temples and chapels, including the temples of Abu Simbel, are in danger of being definitively swallowed up.

In March 1960, UNESCO launched an appeal to save the temples.   Finally, the Swedish-Egyptian proposal was accepted. Starting on April 1, 1964 with the excavation of the cliff around the two temples, Abu Simbel is cut into 1,035 blocks each weighing 20 to 30 tons. The four sitting giants and the six standing ones are sawed into pieces.

Cranes and winches of exceptional power are used to raise these huge masses up to 64 meters high and regroup the blocks so as to recreate exactly the two temples at the top of the cliff. Artificial hills are then built to surround and cap the sanctuaries. On September 22, 1968, the displacement of the temples of Abu Simbel ended, which lasted 4 years.
